Interface NormalizedFunctionCallers


  • public interface NormalizedFunctionCallers
    This interface with no abstract or default methods that bundles a set of static methods which call normalized functions (including static methods and bound instance methods as well as non-class functions defined by lambda expressions) with the number of args appropriate to the normalized function, and either retur a value or fail depending on the expectation as to whether the call will return normally or throw an exception.

    Methods that expect the function it is calling with the specified arguments to return a value are named getReturnValueFrom<function-type>. They either return the value returned by the called function or throw a junit assertion error via a call to AssertionTools.failWithExceptionF(java.lang.String, java.lang.Object...).

    Methods that expect the function it is calling with the specified arguments to throw an exception are named getExceptionFrom<function-type>. They either return (as a value) the exception thrown by the called function or throw a junit assertion error via a call to AssertionTools.failF(java.lang.String, java.lang.Object...).

    The function types accepted by the methods are of two kinds: VFunctions ("voidable" functions) and NormFunctions (normalized functions). There is only one getValueFrom and one getExceptionFrom method for VFunctions that take a given number of arguments, but there may be several overloaded methods for NormFunctions that take a given number of arguments, one for each standard or supplementary Java function type that normalizes to the same normalized type (for example Runnable, Callable<R> and Supplier<R> for getValueFromNoArgNormFunction and getExceptionFromNoArgNormFunction, and Consumer<A> and Function<A,R> for getValueFromOneArgNormFunction and getExceptionFromArgNormFunction.)

    A paralled set of static methods, applicable to VUnboundMethods ("voidable" unbound methods) and NormUnboundMethods (normalized unbound methods) are bundled in the interface NormalizedUnboundMethodCallers.

    Author:
    John Armstrong
